</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F19FF8EFF26FD0FFD3EFAE9" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F19FF8EFF26FD0FFE97FCD2" blockId="44.[151,1437,613,1288]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
Morphology. D VI + I,8–11; A I,7–9; 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F19FF8EFD94FD0FFD33FD42" bold="true" box="[629,723,649,675]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">P 16–18</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F19FF8EFD02FD0FFC8FFD42" author="Miller, P. J." box="[739,879,649,675]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="305 - 334" refId="ref61216" refString="Miller, P. J. (1971) A revision of the Mediterranean gobiid genus Chromogobius (Teleostei Perciformes). Journal of Zoology, London, 164, 305 - 334. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 7998.1971. tb 01321. x" type="journal article" year="1971">Miller 1971</bibRefCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F19FF8EFC62FD0FFD58FD26" bold="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Small goby with elongate body. Head clearly depressed (distinctly dorsoventrally flattened)</emphasis>
, head and predorsal profile horizontal (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F19FF8EFB8EFD2BFB2FFD26" box="[1135,1231,685,711]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1701,1725]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1658]" captionTargetId="figure-18@25.[151,1436,181,1677]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 23. Head clearly depressed (dorsoventrally flattened). A) Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photo by M. Colombo. B) Chromogobius zebratus, photo by M. Kovačić, photographed in a tank." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601641" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601641/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 23a</figureCitation>
). Snout prominent and mouth opening upwards (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F19FF8EFE00FD57FDA1FD0A" box="[481,577,721,747]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1701,1725]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1658]" captionTargetId="figure-18@25.[151,1436,181,1677]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 23. Head clearly depressed (dorsoventrally flattened). A) Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photo by M. Colombo. B) Chromogobius zebratus, photo by M. Kovačić, photographed in a tank." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601641" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601641/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 23a</figureCitation>
). Caudal peduncle deep, almost as high as body. Dorsal fins of similar height, the first dorsal fin may be slightly higher in appearance, with more or less rounded shape and no elongate spines. Caudal fin rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F19FF8EFF26FCBBFE96FBCE" blockId="44.[151,1437,613,1288]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
Live coloration. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F19FF8EFE64FCBBFEBDFC9A" bold="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Body fawn, brown or blackish with a broad pale predorsal bar extending ventrally on pectoral-fin base</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F19FF8EFE8BFCE7FE5CFC9A" box="[362,444,865,891]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1399,1423]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 24. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photos by A) S. Engin, Aegean Sea, Turkey and B) M. Colombo, Area Marina Protetta Capo Caccia-Isola Piana, Alghero, Sardinia, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601645" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601645/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
), in some specimens indistinct. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F19FF8EFCF6FCE7FAFDFC9A" bold="true" box="[791,1309,865,891]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">No pale saddle at origin of the first dorsal fin</emphasis>
, prominent to poorly visible white saddle at origin of the second dorsal fin (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F19FF8EFCB8FC03FC58FC7E" box="[857,952,901,927]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1399,1423]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 24. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photos by A) S. Engin, Aegean Sea, Turkey and B) M. Colombo, Area Marina Protetta Capo Caccia-Isola Piana, Alghero, Sardinia, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601645" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601645/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 24a</figureCitation>
), while another short saddle may be present below posterior part of that fin (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F19FF8EFE19FC2FFDBAFC25" box="[504,602,937,964]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1399,1423]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 24. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photos by A) S. Engin, Aegean Sea, Turkey and B) M. Colombo, Area Marina Protetta Capo Caccia-Isola Piana, Alghero, Sardinia, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601645" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601645/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 24b</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F19FF8EFD8DFC2FFA7CFC22" bold="true" box="[620,1436,937,963]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Tip of lower jaw, top of snout and interorbital space grayish or white.</emphasis>
Head usually with reticulate pattern, including cheeks (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F19FF8EFCE4FC4BFC85FC06" box="[773,869,973,999]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1399,1423]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 24. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photos by A) S. Engin, Aegean Sea, Turkey and B) M. Colombo, Area Marina Protetta Capo Caccia-Isola Piana, Alghero, Sardinia, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601645" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601645/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 24a</figureCitation>
), or cheeks densely dotted (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F19FF8EFB7EFC4BFB1EFC06" box="[1183,1278,973,999]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1701,1725]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1658]" captionTargetId="figure-18@25.[151,1436,181,1677]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 23. Head clearly depressed (dorsoventrally flattened). A) Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photo by M. Colombo. B) Chromogobius zebratus, photo by M. Kovačić, photographed in a tank." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601641" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601641/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 23a</figureCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F19FF8EFAF4FC4BFEB5FBEA" author="Colombo, M. &amp; Langeneck, J." pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="101 - 110" refId="ref52673" refString="Colombo, M. &amp; Langeneck, J. (2013) The importance of underwater photography in detecting cryptobenthic species: new in situ records of some gobies (Teleostei: Gobiidae) from Italian Seas with ecological notes. Acta Adriatica, 54 (1), 101 - 110." type="journal article" year="2013">Colombo &amp; Langeneck 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F19FF8EFE80FC77FD7BFBEA" author="Boltachev, A. R. &amp; Karpova, E. P." box="[353,667,1009,1036]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref52296" refString="Boltachev, A. R. &amp; Karpova, E. P. (2017) Marine fishes of the Crimean Peninsula, second edition. Business-Inform, Simpheropol, 376 pp." type="book" year="2017">Boltachev &amp; Karpova 2017</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F19FF8EFD49FC77FC90FBEA" author="Trkov, D. &amp; Mavric, B. &amp; Orlando-Bonaca, M. &amp; Lipej, L." box="[680,880,1009,1036]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="59 - 72" refId="ref65518" refString="Trkov, D., Mavric, B., Orlando-Bonaca, M. &amp; Lipej, L. (2019) Marine cryptobenthic fish fauna of Slovenia (Northern Adriatic Sea). Annales, Series Historia Naturalis, 29 (1), 59 - 72. https: // doi. org / 10.19233 / ASHN. 2019.07" type="journal article" year="2019">
Trkov 
